===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm}} {{term|crien|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|fro}} {{term|crier|lang=fro}}, {{gloss|"to announce publicly, proclaim, scream, shout"; > {{etyl|ML.|-}} {{term|cridare|crīdāre|to cry out, shout, publish, proclaim|lang=la}}}}, of {{etyl|gem}} origin, from Old {{etyl|frk}} {{recons|kritan|krītan|to cry, cry out, publish|lang=frk}}, from {{proto|Germanic|krītanan|to cry out, shout|lang=en}}, from {{proto|Indo-European|greid-|to shout|lang=en}}. Cognate with {{etyl|nl|-}} {{term|krijten||to cry|lang=nl}}, {{etyl|gml|-}} {{term|kriten|krīten|to cry, call out, shriek|lang=ang}}, {{etyl|de|-}} {{term|kreissen||to cry loudly, wail, groan|lang=de}}, {{etyl|got|-}} {{term|𐌺𐍂𐌴𐌹𐍄𐌴𐌽||tr=kreitan|to cry, scream, call out|lang=got}}, {{etyl|mga|-}} {{term|grith||a cry|lang=mga}}, {{etyl|cy|-}} {{term|gryd||a scream|lang=cy}}.

{{rel-top|etymology note}}
Alternate etymology connects the {{etyl|ML.|-}} word to {{etyl|la|-}} {{term|queri||to complain|lang=la}} through the form {{term|quiritare||to wail, shriek|lang=la}}, though the phonetic and semantic developments are difficult to trace.

Middle English {{term|crien}} eventually displaced native Middle English {{term|galen||to cry out|lang=enm}} (from Old English {{term|galan||lang=ang}}), Middle English {{term|greden||to cry out|lang=enm}} (from Old English {{term|grædan|grǣdan|sc=Latinx|lang=ang}}), Middle English {{term|yermen||to bellow, mourn, lament|lang=enm}} (from Old English {{term|gierman|ġierman|lang=ang}}), Middle English {{term|hoen|hooen, hoen|to cry out|lang=enm}} (from Old Norse {{term|hoa|hōa|lang=non}}), Middle English {{term|remen||to cry, shout|lang=enm}} (from Old English {{term|hrieman|hrīeman|lang=ang}}, compare Old English {{term|hream|hrēam|noise, outcry, lamentation, alarm|lang=ang}}), Middle English {{term|gretan|greten, graten|to weep, cry, lament|lang=enm}} (from Old English {{term|grætan|grǣtan|sc=Latinx|lang=ang}} and Old Norse {{term|grata|grāta|lang=non}}). More at [[greet]], [[regret]].
{{rel-bottom}}

